﻿Collective Bargaining Agreement
Between Felipe's Tortillería (the “Employer”) and Tortillería Workers Union Local 100 (the “Union”)
 Effective: January 1, 2025 – December 31, 2028
Article 1. Recognition
1. The Employer recognizes the Union as the exclusive bargaining representative of all production employees, tortilla makers, packagers, cleaners, and delivery assistants employed at Felipe's Tortillería in Walla Walla, Washington, excluding managers, supervisors, and confidential employees.

2. This Agreement covers approximately ten (10) bargaining unit employees.

Article 2. Union Rights
   1. Union Security: Employees have the right to join or not join the Union. No employee shall be discriminated against for union membership or protected activity.

   2. Union Dues Checkoff: Upon voluntary written authorization, the Employer shall deduct union dues and remit them monthly to the Union.

   3. Union Access: Union representatives shall be granted reasonable access to the workplace fo

r meetings, provided they do not disrupt production.

   4. Bulletin Board: A designated space will be provided for posting union notices.

   5. Steward Rights: Stewards may investigate grievances during paid time with notice to management.

Article 3. Management Rights
The Employer retains the right to manage operations, schedule work, hire, discipline, and direct employees, except as limited by this Agreement.
Article 4. Equal Employment Opportunity
      1. The Employer and Union shall comply with the Washington Equal Pay and Opportunities Act (EPOA), ensuring equal pay for substantially similar work regardless of gender or protected class.

      2. Promotion opportunities, pay ranges, and job postings will be shared internally.

      3. No employee shall be discriminated against based on race, color, creed, religion, sex, gender identity, sexual orientation, national origin, immigration or citizenship status, veteran status, age, or disability.

Article 5. Wages
         1. Mini

mum Wages: No employee shall be paid less than the Washington State minimum wage in effect during the contract.

            * As of Jan 1, 2025, WA minimum wage is $17.10/hour (indexed annually).

               2. Wage Scale:

                  * Entry-Level Worker (first 6 months): $18.00/hour

                  * Tortilla Maker: $19.50/hour

                  * Delivery/Packaging Lead: $20.50/hour

                  * Senior Employee (2+ years): $21.50/hour

                  * Food Safety Certified Worker: +$0.50/hour premium

                  * Bilingual Customer-Facing Worker: +$0.50/hour premium

                     3. Overtime: Hours worked beyond 40 in a week shall be paid at 1.5x the regular rate, per RCW 49.46.130.

                     4. Overtime Distribution: Overtime opportunities will be offered by seniority on a rotating basis.

                     5. Shift Differentials:

                        * Night shifts (work starting after 8:00 p.m.): additional $1.00/hour

.

                        * Sunday shifts: additional $0.50/hour.

                           6. Pay Period: Biweekly via direct deposit.

Article 6. Hours of Work & Scheduling
                              1. Workweek: Sunday through Saturday.

                              2. Shifts: Standard shifts are 8 hours, with at least 10 hours of rest between shifts unless mutually agreed.

                              3. Breaks:

                                 * Paid 10-minute break for every 4 hours worked.

                                 * Unpaid 30-minute meal period for shifts over 5 hours.

                                 * Missed breaks will be paid as time worked.

                                    4. Scheduling Notice: Employees will receive their weekly schedule at least 7 days in advance.

                                       * If schedules are changed within 72 hours (without employee consent), affected employees will receive one (1) additional hour of premium pay.

5. Call-In Minimum: Any employee called in outside the schedule will be guaranteed at least 3 hours’ pay.

Article 7. Probationary Period
                                             1. New employees shall serve a 60-day probationary period.

                                             2. During probation, employees may be disciplined or terminated without recourse to the grievance procedure. After probation, full contractual rights apply.

Article 8. Paid & Unpaid Leave
                                                1. Sick Leave:

                                                   * Accrual at 1 hour per 40 hours worked, per Washington Paid Sick Leave law.

                                                   * Unused sick leave carries over up to 40 hours per year.

                                                      2. Vacation Leave:

                                                         * 1 week paid vacation after 1 year of service.

* 2 weeks after 3 years.

                                                         * 3 weeks after 6 years.

                                                            3. Holidays (Paid): New Year’s Day, Memorial Day, Independence Day, Labor Day, Thanksgiving, Christmas, Día de los Muertos.

                                                            4. Personal Days: 2 floating holidays per year.

                                                            5. Family & Medical Leave: Employees eligible under Washington PFML may take leave with job protection.

Article 9. Benefits
                                                               1. Health Coverage: Employer contributes $250/month toward employee health insurance premiums for employees working 30+ hours/week.

                                                               2. Retirement: Employer will establish a SIMPLE IRA and contribute up to 2% of wages for employee

s who participate.

                                                               3. Uniform Allowance: Employer will provide two branded shirts per year and reimburse up to $75 annually for shoes or uniforms.

                                                               4. Transit Benefit: Employer provides up to $50/month toward public transportation costs.

                                                               5. Product Benefit: Employees receive two free tortillas per shift and 25% discount on all products.

Article 10. Health & Safety
                                                                  1. Employer shall comply with all Washington Industrial Safety and Health Act (WISHA) standards.

                                                                  2. Proper PPE (aprons, gloves, slip-resistant shoes, masks when necessary) shall be provided by the Employer.

                                                                  3. Employees shall have the right

to refuse unsafe work without retaliation.

                                                                  4. Joint Health & Safety Committee: A labor-management group shall meet quarterly to review hazards, accidents, and improvements.

Article 11. Seniority
                                                                     1. Seniority is defined as the length of continuous employment in the bargaining unit.

                                                                     2. Seniority governs layoffs, recalls, shift preferences, promotions, and overtime assignment where skill and ability are substantially equal.

Article 12. Discipline & Discharge
                                                                        1. No employee shall be disciplined or discharged without just cause.

                                                                        2. Discipline shall follow progressive steps: verbal warning, written warning, suspension, discharge.

3. Employees may request a union steward present during disciplinary meetings.

Article 13. Subcontracting & Bargaining Unit Work
                                                                           1. Employer shall not subcontract or outsource tortilla production or packaging work without negotiating with the Union.

                                                                           2. Bargaining unit work shall not be regularly performed by supervisors, managers, or temporary employees, except for training or emergencies.

Article 14. Grievance & Arbitration
                                                                              1. A grievance is any dispute regarding the interpretation or application of this Agreement.

                                                                              2. Procedure:

                                                                                 * Step 1: Info

rmal discussion with supervisor.

                                                                                 * Step 2: Written grievance to Employer within 14 days.

                                                                                 * Step 3: If unresolved, arbitration under AAA Labor Arbitration Rules.

                                                                                    3. Arbitration decisions shall be final and binding.

Article 15. No-Strike / No-Lockout
                                                                                       1. During the life of this Agreement, the Union shall not strike, and the Employer shall not lock out employees.

                                                                                       2. This does not restrict the right to strike after contract expiration.

Article 16. Successorship
                                                                                          1. If ownership of the

tortillería changes, the Agreement remains in effect until expiration or renegotiation.

                                                                                          2. The Employer agrees to require any purchaser, transferee, or successor to recognize the Union and assume this Agreement as a condition of sale.

Article 17. Duration
This Agreement shall be in effect from January 1, 2025, to December 31, 2028, and shall automatically renew unless either party gives 60 days’ written notice of intent to modify or terminate.
